column168: This drum was picked up from the generator, Econo Paint and Body, in Memphis TN. The Sales and Service Rep that accepted this drum failed to do a proper container inspection and verify proper closure of the drum. This drum was transported through a number of facilities prior to the release in Baton Rouge. The drum was loaded improperly and was not secured adequately. The drum shifted during transport. While being unloaded, an attempt was made to square the drum up on the pallet. During this effort the drum slipped and fell off the pallet and the improperly tightened open top closure failed to contain the material allowing 35 gallons to be released to the trailer floor.
column169: The affected drum was over-packed in a salvage drum and material used to remediate the affected surfaces were included in the salvage drum. The Sales and Service Rep that originally accepted the drum will receive remedial training regarding proper container inspection and container closure. The facilities that this drum traveled through including the last facility where the drum was improperly loaded and inadequately secured will receive remedial training in proper loading, container inspection, drum closure and proper load securement.

column168: On September 2, 2021, at approximately 3:40 a.m. CDT, a representative from R+L Carriers (RLC) discovered one (1) damaged 50-pound bag of UN3378 that was punctured by the skid. As a result, approximately ten (10) pounds of product released to the interior surfaces of the trailer. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental, LLC (FCE) to perform the necessary corrective action. FCE personnel containerized the damaged bag and all free product into one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal.

column168: The drum was discovered leaking on a trailer that was parked in a 10 day storage area and was reported to the management team by a driver that was dispatched to transport the trailer. The affected drum was the only drum on this load that contained the listed material. The material 6 RQ, UN1992, Waste Flammable Liquids, Toxic, N.O.S. Mixture, (Ethylene Dichloride, 1-Bromo-2-Chloroethane), 3 (6.1), PG11 (F025 (1 LB.)), according to the HMT and regulation regarding authorized packagings, was contained in an authorized drum. The material appeared to have corroded the drum, which appeared to be a new drum, to the extent that the material started to leach through the drum.
column169: The drum was over packed in a salvage drum and the material used to clean up and remediated soil from area effected by the leak was included in the salvage drum. The drum appeared to be a new drum and there was no visible abnormality regarding the drum upon the initial container inspection. The material, despite being in an authorized container, appears to have corroded and deteriorated the drum wall construction to the point of allowing the material to leach out of the drum. The generator has been contacted regarding this occurrence and will be reevaluating packaging of this material in the future.

column168: At 0747 on Friday, September 10 PTRA Director of Mechanical Maintenance reported product leaking from the UTLX 210496 around the bottom outlet valve. Slick Response Services was dispatched to the scene and arrived at 0817. Upon inspection of the tank car they found product was leaking around the packing nut on the bottom outlet valve handle. Slick Response noted that the nut was backed off 1/4 to 1/2 inch on the threads. They tightened the packing nut and observed the car for several minutes and determined that the leak was stopped. Slick Response then remediated the area beneath the car.   Chemtrec was notified at 0805 hours, incident number 2021091000100
column169: The UTLX 210496 was shipped by Tauber Oil care of Intercontinental Terminals in Deer Park, TX. ITC Representative Karl Kuhn was made aware of the situation and will conduct further investigation as deemed necessary.

column25: Bravo Energy Mexico SRL de CV
column168: Oil and Carbon was packaged in one box together and sent to Mott by ground out of Mexico. According to the customer (and pictures were sent), the carbon was bagged and shrink wrapped. When it crossed U.S. Customs Border, Customs ripped it open so the carbon spilled within the box and left it. As it continued in transit, the Carbon black got everywhere in the box and when it arrived at Mott there were trace amounts you could see coming out of the corners of the boxes. The box was not UN rated and was not labeled or shipped properly.
column169: At the border, there should be a HazMat auditor in addition to Customs, especially if Customs is going to be ripping hazardous material open to check it.

FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE AND EMITTING AN ALCOHOL-LIKE ODOR BY THE LVD PICK-OFF ON THE PD-1. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE CUT OFF THE POWER TO THE CONVEYOR BELT, EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN A FEW MINUTES A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 1 PLASTIC 1-GAL JUG WAS LOOSE BY 1/2 ROTATION, CAUSING APPROX. 6 OZ OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 275 LBS LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.

column168: Shipper's container failed causing product to leak during transport.

On 9/14/2021 at 1400 personnel in the CSXT Russell Yard discovered HOKX112353, a loaded tank car  of Sodium Hydroxide Solution that had a pressure relief device activate. The car was isolated and Occidental  Chemical, Kentucky Dept of Environmental Conservation, and the National Response Center were  notified CHEMTREC Report #2021-09-14-00272. Quick Response, a CSXT response contractor, was  dispatched to the scene and found the pressure relief device that had activated. The issue identified  and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Justin Smith, OxyChem, 931-535-4421.  Contractor personnel neutralized the dried product to the tank car and cleared the site. The activation  of the pressure relief device was found to be from the over handling of the car while in transport. The  pressure relief device reset and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a  special switching move.
column169: (nar code:1006 2  What Failed: Non-Reclosing Pressure Relief Device  Where Failed: Opening in center of pressure relief device or under pressure  relief cap/cover  Why Failed: Frangible disc ruptured; no surge suppressor; no ss expected

column168: On September 2, 2021 at 0901 ET XPO Logistics Terminal XFW notified ERTS of a cargo release of DaaFit Plus from a 50 pound paper bag, impacting the trailer floor. ERTS dispatched ERS to the site to complete cleanup. At 1550 EST, ERS personnel arrived onsite and confirmed 1 pound of product released to a 1' x 5' & 1' x 1' area of the trailer floor due to the seams on the paper bags failing. The material was collected and containerized into a 5 gallon poly drum. The bags were then containerized into a cubic yard box and a supersack for continued shipment. All waste was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On 2 Sep 21, at 1827 ET, ABF called ERTS to report that a 55 gallon poly drum of UN3264 (trade name HyproBlue) was punctured in a trailer.  All 55 gallons released in the trailer and down into the yard below.  ERTS dispatched Hepaco out of Monroe, MI to respond.  At 2013 ET, Hepaco arrived on site and assessed the area. Hepaco found the 55 gallon poly drum of "Hyproblue" was punctured on the bottom and lost all 55 gallons. 42' x 8' area in the trailer is impacted as well as a 8' x 10' area on the asphalt below. Of the 55 gallons released, 5 gallons released outside of the trailer. Sodium Bicarb solution will be used to neutralize the product and oil dry will be used to clean. The damaged drum will be overpacked into a 95 gallon poly drum.  Hepaco finished cleanup and are departing site with the waste. 1-95 gallon poly overpack containing the damaged drum empty and 1-55 gallon poly drum of neutralized absorbents were generated.
column169: This is considered a one-time incident.

On September 14, 2021 at 0911 ET, XPO Logistics (XAY terminal) contacted ERTS regarding a UN1993, Flammable Liquid, N.O.S., 3, PG III "Unisol Liquid Red BK-50" release that occurred at 0845 ET. It was advised that 1/2 gallon of product release from the top seal on a 275 gallon steel tote on the dock. An ERTS network contractor dispatch was requested. At 1218 EST, Hepaco arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 0.5 gallons of product released from the top seal to the tote itself. Hepaco advised that the bolt on the top lid was not tightened properly and they were able to secure it. The tote was slosh tested for shipment onto the customer. The impacted absorbents generated were placed into a 30 gallon poly drum which was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

At 0908 ET, XPO Logistics terminal XSA contacted ERTS regarding the release of UN3266 corrosive liquid. It was reported that a box of 1 gallon jugs arrived damaged and released an unknown amount of material onto the trailer floor. ERTS has dispatched Hepaco to conduct cleanup. At 1325 EST Hepaco personnel arrived onsite and confirmed that a 1 gallon poly jug of UN3266 Nu-Brite Coil Cleaner was punctured and released approximately 1/2 gallon of product onto the trailer floor and onto the two other boxes in the shipment. The impacted area of the trailer floor was neutralized and cleaned with absorbents. The four bottles of Nu-Brite, impacted absorbents and the impacted pallet were placed into a 55 gallon poly drum. The impacted box of UN2920 Easy Seal Ultimate LS and a box of impacted non-regulated Great Wipes were each placed into separate 55 gallon poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO Logistics called ERTS to report a release of 8 gallons of hazardous UN3266 Zep Driveway Concrete Cleaner. ERTS dispatched a contractor to conduct cleanup and overpacking. At 2250 EST E3 personnel arrived onsite and observed several boxes that had fallen off of 2 pallets that appeared to be double stacked. According to E3, Zep Driveway Concrete Cleaner was the only product that was damaged and leaking. There were several boxes that were impacted. The boxes (just boxes, no product) were placed into a waste drum for disposal. The jugs that were undamaged, but out of their boxes were wiped down and placed on the restacked pallet to be forwarded on, no material impacted the floor, as the boxes caught all the released product. The impacted cardboard, PPE and spill pads were placed into a 55 gallon poly drum which was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On September 14, 2021 at 0420 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal XMI called to report a release from a 55 gallon drum of a UN1263 "BPANI Non Stick Enamel KO051J" which was punctured by a fork blade, releasing 25 gallons to the trailer floor. ERTS dispatched EnviroServe to conduct cleanup activities. On September 14, 2021 at 0830 EST, EnviroServe personnel arrived onsite and confirmed 20 gallons of product impacted an 8' x 10' area of the trailer and a 1' x 1' area of the asphalt below. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and collected into a 55 gallon metal drum. The damaged drum was overpacked into an 85 gallon poly drum. All waste was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: At 0813 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics (LJB) about a cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading, approximately 12 gallons of LambdaStar 1EC(Plus) - (Hazardous - UN3352) was released. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer floor at dock door #5. The terminal requested a contractor out due to the hazardous (toxic) state of the product. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to conduct all cleanup operations. At 1225 EST, Hepaco personnel arrived onsite and confirmed 10 gallons of product released to a 6' x 6' area of the dock floor as well as impacting the other boxes in the shipment. Absorbents were worked into all impacted areas and collected. All boxes and jugs were containerized along with spent absorbents into (4) 55 gallon poly and (2) 55 gallon metal drums. A total of (17) 1 gallon jugs were confirmed to have been damaged or releasing and (4) cases of (4) 1 gallon jugs were unaffected and staged on a pallet for shipment.

At 0541 ET, XPO Logistics notified ERTS of a cargo release at XWK. It was reported that 40 gallons of UN1993 was released from a 55 gallon metal drum due to a forklift accident. The majority of the contents of the drum released, impacting the trailer floor and the underlying asphalt. The terminal was able to tip the drum over and control the leak before it reached any other mediums. At the request of XPO, ERTS dispatched a contractor. At 0945 EST, Haz-Mat Response arrived onsite and confirmed 40 gallons of product impacted an 8' x 8' area of the trailer floor and a 60' x 6' area of the asphalt lot below the trailer. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and collected. Contractors overpacked the impacted drum into an 85 gallon metal overpack and containerized all spent absorbents into (2) 55 gallon steel drums. The crew also advised they located 2 boxes of Windshield Washer RTU in cardboard boxes that were soaked by the release and placed these boxes into (2) 5 gallon poly pails. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On 9/14/2021 at 1400 personnel in the CSXT Russell Yard discovered (Car initial and number), a  residue tank car of Fluorosilic Acid leaking from pressure relief vent. The car was isolated and Solvay  Chemical, KDEP, and National Response Center were notified CHEMTREC Report #2021-09-14-00258.  SPSI, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the faulty pressure relief  device. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Cindy Shirley and  618-215-7151. Contractor personnel replaced the pressure relief vent and were unable to get the car  to pass a bubble leak test. Once the car was above 5 PSI a small leak was detected coming around  the rupture disk. The car was depressurized and is currently awaiting to be clean and purged, so it can  move on an OTMA. It was determined that the lining in the car is preventing the PRV from sealing  correctly. This incident did not require a special switching move.

Should never have left Milwaukee station under those conditions. Refer to F-track. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: the damaged package that was put in a lined hazmat bin was taken care of by admin in the following manner: package was covered and ventilated for approx.8 hours. At 0122ET, XPO Logistics notified ERTS of an active cargo release at XTM. It was reported that "Low Volume 6 Ester Weed Killer" released from a 30 gallon poly drum due to a forklift accident. The release occurred on the trailer but material leaked outside the trailer. The terminal used oil dri to contain the release and requested a response, ERTS dispatched a network contractor to respond for cleanup operations. At 0615 EST WRR personnel arrived onsite and confirmed 30 gallons of product released to an 8' x 20' area of the trailer, 8' x 50' area of the concrete, and a 1' x 20' area of the asphalt. The crew swept absorbents into all the impacted areas to collect the material. The damaged drum was placed into a 55 gallon poly overpack. Impacted pallets were cut up and containerized into another 55 gallon poly drum. All impacted absorbents were collected and containerized along with any additional cleanup debris into (3) 55 gallon poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

HOLDING ALL PRODUCT AND PACKAGING UNTIL RELEASE IS ISSUED.

UNLOADING PKG FROM UPS TRAILER AND FOUND LEAKING PKG ON FLOOR SITTING IN PROPER POSITION WITH ARROWS. DESIGNATED RESPONDER IDENTIFIED CONTENTS AND MOVED PKG TO DAMAGE PROCESSING AREA. PULLED UP THE SDS AND DETERMINED FROM AREA 14 THAT CONTENTS DID NOT HAVE PROPER OUTER CARTON LABELING. CONTACTED ADG HAZMAT HELP DESK TO VERIFY. HOLDING CONTENTS AND PACKAGING FOR RELEASE FROM ADG FOR CUSTOMER TO PICKUP AT UPS TERMINAL.

All impacted absorbents were then collected and containerized into (3) 55 gallon metal drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: BNSF employees identified the NATX 302347 with wetness on the tank shell and slowly dripping from the car in Track 04 (Denver, CO). column168: On 9/17/2021 at 1726 personnel in the CSXT Russell, KY discovered GATX94689, a loaded tank car of  Isopropylbenzene leaking from liquid line flange. The car was isolated and (Marathon Petroleum  Company, KDEP and Nation Response Center were notified (CHEMTREC Report #20210917-00315.  Quick Response, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a liquid leak  coming from the liquid line flange connection to the fittings plate. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Mike Murray-606-921-6255. Contractor personnel vented the pressure off the car and secure the car for a mobile repair unit top inspect the flange/valve.  The impaction to the car evaporated and did not require further decontamination. On 9/20/2021 Specialized Professional Services inspected the flange/ valve and found that the flange bolts were  torqued to <50ft lbs. The normal torque spec for these flanges bolts is 150ft lbs. After the  flange/valve was torque to the proper spec, the car was pressured to 35 psi with nitrogen. There  were no leaks detected by SPSI once the flange/valve was torqued to the proper spec. The car is  currently awaiting an OTMA-1 to return to Marathon to be bubble leak tested. This incident did not  require a special switching move.

column168: Tank Car TCIX 210114 was observed by a train crew leaking a yellow liquid that caked/crystallized into a yellow solid on the stub sill and ground.  NS Hazmat and Hepaco, a response contractor, performed an assessment on the car and found the liquid was coming out of the jacket in multiple places on the B-end end of the car.  The contents of the leaking car were transferred into tank trailers and a poly tank that was brought in for storage.  The car was purged and cleaned, then the B-end of the jacket was cut away to expose the source of the leak.  A crack was found where the hand brake bracket was welded directly to the tank head.

column168: During switching operations, yard crew reported leak coming from the manway on TILX 312368 anytime it was moved.  Car was setout to isolation track.  NS Hazmat and Hepaco, a response contractor, responded to investigate and repair the car.  The manway bolts were found to be tool tight but there were signs of leakage around manway.  Manway was opened and the manway lid gasket was not properly seated in the grooved portion of the lid as designed.  Approximately 80% of the gasket was not seated in the manway lid and was hanging down into the car.  The gasket showed signs of being folded and torn.  A replacement lid gasket was not available therefore a manway nozzle gasket was installed to seal the manway.  The manway was secured and tool tightened.  The valve cover was opened and the valves were inspected with no defects found.  The car was released back into transportation.

column168: Yard crew reported an odor smelling like super glue in the area of UTLX 203407 at Charlotte Yard. The crew departed and the car was isolated.  NS Hazmat and Hepaco, a response contractor, responded to investigate and repair the car.  Elevated VOC readings were detected around the valve plate housing.  High VOC readings detected around the sample line denoting a leak.  The sample line valve was 1/2 turn open and the sample line plug turned easily by hand.  The sample line valve was closed and the plug was tool tightened.  No other defects were found on the car.  The car was released for transportation.

On 9/13/2021, at 1120 hours, personnel in the CSXT South Charleston Yard PROX 24113, a residue tank car of Styrene Monomer, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection, and the National Response Center were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2021-0913-00129). Quick Response, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a vapor release emanating from the base of the liquid valve flange connection to the fittings plate.. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Mr. Chad Blake of Covestro, LLC, phone 304-281-4864. Contractor personnel depressured the car, and removed all residue from the fittings plate. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.   Cause Code: 279 NARRI: 50
UNDETERMNED

Contractors collected and containerized the damaged drum into one (1) 95-gallons overpacked poly drum and all clean-up debris into thirteen (13) 55-gallons poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: During the loading process at the destination terminal, the tote was damaged when other freight was pushed into the tote, causing a crack in the tote. The forklift operator loading freight failed to place a dunnage pallet up against the tote to protect the tote. As other freight was being loaded behind it, the freight slid forward too far, pressing up against the tote and causing the damage. The material released into the trailer was neutralized and absorbed using absorbent material. The collected contents were placed into a drum for later disposal. The package specifications were unable to be obtained.
column169: This incident may have been prevented if a dunnage pallet was placed in front of the tote to protect it. The forklift operator has been counseled per company policy about using proper blocking and bracing techniques when loading freight. This incident may be used in future safety discussion topics to illustrate the importance of proper blocking and bracing techniques.

Highway Transport (HT) driver discovered that his trailer was leaking after he ran over a piece of tire in the roadway and stopped to see if any damages had been caused as a result. Driver noticed liquid dripping out of the drain tube from the crash box. After climbing on top of the trailer and seeing product in the crash box, it was determined first determined that a valve had been left open. After approximately an hour of driving HT driver stopped again to check for leaks. Driver discovered trailer was still leaking from somewhere in the crash box. Driver called in to HT safety department to notify of the leak. Environmental Management (EMI) was dispatched to the location of the equipment. When EMI arrived and assessed the trailer, they found that the gasket for the dome lid was missing. EMI installed a new gasket and resealed the trailer. Product that was inside of the crash box cleaned up by EMI and HT driver was released to continue to load origin.
column169: Highway Transport driver was coached on performing better Pre-Trip Inspections prior to loading trailers, and Highway Transport also met with tank wash facility (Proclean) to ensure they pay more attention to detail (gaskets) when prepping trailers.

column168: A HAZMAT PACKAGE FELL OFF THE BELT ACROSS FROM DOOR 18   STARTED TO LEAK. THE SUPERVISOR SAW THE LEAK   CALLED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER. WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. I CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY   USED ABSORBENT TO SOLIDIFY THE LIQUID ON THE GRATING. I SWEPT UP THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT   ADDED IT TO THE SPILL TRAY. I THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, I FOUND THAT 1 BOTTLE HAD CRACKED   HAD SOILED THE REMAINING 3 BOTTLES.
CAME TO RECEIVE THIS PACKAGE AND WAS TOLD IT WAS LEAKING AND HAD STAINED THE BOX. GRABBED IT AND PROCESSED IT OUT.
TRAILER OPENED AND HAD SMELL. NO PACKAGE FOUND LATER APPEARED ON BELT 2

Univar Solutions; Material Handler attempted to load Tanker 11646 that was already loaded. This resulted in an overflow of approximately 200 gals of Sodium Hypochlorite solution to spill onto the loading pad containment. The material was collected and the area cleaned. No injuries, exposures, or offsite impacts occurred. Tanker 11646 was loaded by the Material Handler earlier in the week but that customer canceled their order leaving the product in the tanker.  Material Handler called for Tanker 11646 to be spotted at loading station by yardman.  Material Handler failed to recognize tanker was still loaded before filling another order.  Tanker’s dome lid and outlet valves were sealed from prior filling.  Tanker’s outlet valve was also tagged from prior load (indication the tanker was loaded).
column169: The employee was retrained on proper loading procedures. The employee failed to use our bulk tanker loading checklist.  This checklist will be audited going forward with random audits by facility management.

column168: On 9/23/2021 at about 9:30 AM, a Veolia employee entered the back of a box van to offload containers when he noticed a 30 gallon fiber drum of Regulated Medical Waste wet around the bottom of the container. He then asked for assistance from the Veolia, Schenectady, NY facility to overpack the 30 gallon drum.  Once the container was overpacked, the employee then brought it to the Stericycle, Oneonta, NY facility so it could be offloaded there and then sent for proper disposal in Rhode Island. The Veolia employee investigated the source of the leak but could not figure out what caused the leak without opening the container. It is assumed that the liner inside the fiber drum was defective or damaged and allowed liquid to dampen the fiber drum. It is estimated that less than 2 ounces of liquid leaked into the box van. No liquid made it outside of the box van. The drum was overpacked and the liquid on the truck floor was cleaned up.
column169: The Veolia employee investigated the source of the leak but could not figure out what caused the leak without opening the container. It is assumed that the liner inside the fiber drum was defective or damaged and allowed liquid to dampen the fiber drum. The package is better than what is typically used for medical waste. We assume that there was a problem with the plastic liner and it was either punctured or defective but could not perform a detailed inspection of it due to the fact that it was medical waste. We will continue to monitor shipments from this customer as well as others to see if there are any additional issues.

column168: The Driver of the vehicle involved was traveling South on Old Route 8, a 2 lane road with little or no berms, due to the South bound lanes of the 4 lane Route 8 being closed for road construction. Weather conditions were poor due to heavy rainfall. The driver just came out of a sharp bend in the roadway, dropping off the edge onto the soft berm that pulled his unit into the ditch where it came to rest on it's side against a dirt bank and small trees. The driver, who was not injured, was told by another driver who was following him, that 911 had been called. He then assessed the situation and called our company to notify us. I then called the wrecker/recovery service, the remediation/cleanup company, and then the National Response Center (NRC) to advise of the situation in the event of a possible spill. There was no package failure that resulted in a spill. Approximately 20 to 30 gallons was released through the pressure release system during the 2 hours and 30 minutes the unit was on it's side against the bank, until being placed back on it's wheels by the wrecker service. There was no structural or valve failures. Plugs made from rags were placed into the relief tube to stop the venting of product. The spillage was contained in the ditch by pads and dirt. Thankfully, the tank, the dome lid area, and the offload valve were not damaged.
column169: The berm of the roadway and weather conditions were a contributing factor to the cause of this incident. All drivers/employees have been notified as a refresher, to use extreme caution during these conditions, or anytime they travel any roadway. Especially with winter conditions soon to arrive. During these types of weather conditions, it is extremely important to reduce speed and use caution while keeping a safe distance from other vehicles. All drivers/employees were reminded to maintain respect for the transportation of a liquid product that is constantly moving. The tanker transporting the liquid asphalt was in very good condition and well maintained. This contributed to only a small amount of product being released through the pressure release venting tube. The detour route being used, due to the road closure of the main route being under construction, is not the best route of travel for Commercial Vehicles. Very few of our drivers use the designated detour route.

CN Transportation department employee reported product coming from the top of tank car NATX 310573 (L / NA1993 / Combustible Liquid, N.O.S.) during switching operations at the CN Presidents Island Yard, Memphis, TN. All appropriate departments notified, the railcar was isolated. CN's response team responded, upon climbing the railcar for closer inspection, liquid was observed on the railcar manway nozzle.  The manway was secured by a security seal and all manway bolts were found to be tool tight.  The seal was removed and the manway was opened to inspect the manway gasket. The manway gasket showed signs of uneven wear from contact between the manway lid and the manway nozzle gasket sealing surface. The uneven wear was an indication that the gasket was misaligned.  A new manway gasket was installed and car was properly secured and new security seal installed. Car was released for movement to destination.

Much of that was on the pallet and cleaned up from the floor of the trailer. It was below the threshold quantity for any other type of reporting. The entire pallet containing the leaking container was left at the customer's site, and the quantity on the manifest was adjusted to reflect the pallet's removal. column168: HOC Transport notified ERTS of an unknown amount of gasoline that was released from an 8500-gallon tanker due to user error in Twinsburg, OH. It was reported that the driver failed to attach the hose before opening the valve. The release has impacted the pavement of a Circle K, and migrated towards a storm drain. The fire department was on scene containing the spill with oil dri. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor who estimated that approximately 20 gallons released to a 30ft x 10ft area of asphalt. Enviroserve (enviro contractor) personnel have completed the cleanup. They collected all of the impacted absorbents from the parking lot and generated one 55-gallon steel drum of waste, which is being transported offsite for disposal. They opened up the storm drain and did not see any signs of impact. There was no visible sheen or signs of gasoline inside the drain or on the waters surface. An absorbent boom was placed in the drain as a precaution.

column168: A limited quantity dangerous goods shipment of UN1993 Flammable Liquid, N.O.S packing group II was observed leaking during AM sort operations at the FedEx Express destination ramp in Coraopolis, PA. The outer box did have dangerous goods markings and labeling, and a Shippers Declaration for Dangerous Goods was offered with the shipment. The station was directed by Dangerous Goods Administration to have FedEx Spill Cleanup staff contain the shipment in a salvage drum and hold it pending further disposition instruction.

column168: On 9/15/2021 at around 9:15 AM, the Kanas City Southern Railway's(KCS) Environmental& Hazmat Department was notified by KCS personnel working in the KCS Shreveport, LA rail yard, that ACFX 220428(residue BUTADIENE) was emanatlng an odor while in the Car Shop. The car was shoved out of the car shop, and a railroad qualified response contractor was mobilized to investigate. Upon arrival, the contractor donned appropriate PPE& SCBA, and ascended the tank car to perform an inspection of the valves inside the protective housing. ACFX 220428 was found with an audible gas leak Inside protective housing. The Inspection of the vapor line valve revealed that the valve wasn't properly closed, with a vapor pressure that could be felt with a glove hand coming from the top of vapor line dry lock secondary closure plug, emitting pass the cap. Responders tightened the vapor line valve to the fully closed position which stopped the vapor leak. The car was pressure tested at the sample port which revealed 84 psl. The sample port plug was relnstalled and rendered tool tight. Cable seals were applied to both liquid line& vapor line valve handles In a manner to prevent valves from Ioosenlng. Snoop was applied to all valves& leak points inside protective housing, with no additional leaks found. Because the dry lock secondary closure plug was defective, a new dry lock fitting was obtained and Installed prior to the car being released back Into transportation. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the tlme of filing. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered In this package Is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway(KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases(NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adJacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases(a.k.a. package closure Issues such as this), the shipper Is requested to conduct a root-cause Investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It Is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.(Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: Sinclair Truck was traveling west on I-95 when a passenger vehicle swerved to the left over two lanes of traffic and hit the right front tire of the Sinclair Vehicle. The force of the contact caused the Sinclair truck to turn to the left where the left front tire hit the center median and the truck was rolled on to its passenger side. The rollover caused a leak in the trailer which ended up releasing about 500 gallons of gasoline. The fire department responded initially and put cat litter in the road to dam up the small stream of gasoline so that the gasoline did not get into the storm drain system. Later the gasoline was pumped out of the tank trailer and the triler was turned upright and towed to a storage yard. The fuel spill was cleaned up by Clean Harbors with many bags of vermiculite and put into 55 gallon storage drums and taken away for disposal. Driver was not hurt. There is a video from the Sinclair Truck showing the crash.

column168: Forklift operator was loading outbound trailer at SEFL dock. He was attempting to load a transmission into a open space in the trailer and as he was moving forward the forklift blade caught and punctured the corner of the plastic bladder of the IBC. The hole in the bladder was a 4" cut along the middle of the plastic bladder. The liquid spilled onto the trailer floor, dock and dock apron for a short duration of time as the associates plugged the hole with some plastic material to slow the leak. At this point they were able to remove the IBC from the trailer and place it on the dock at an angle to stop the release. Once the leak was stopped they waited on the response team to arrive. The spilled liquid had leaked onto flat surfaces and was not spreading in any direction. Hazmat One was contacted around 18:37 to send a response team to mitigate the spill. They arrived on scene and began the clean up. They transferred the remaining liquid from the damaged IBC into a new tank which was about 200 gallons. They contained and cleaned up all contaminated ares that had spilled material present. All clean up material was properly packed for disposal. All material clean up was taken by the Hazmat One response team for disposal.

column168: At 445pm, William Siano driver heading East on Belews Creek Rd in Stokesdale, NC going 45 mph in a 35 mph and drifted off road to the right, then tried to over compensate which caused the tanker to roll and flip the tractor. We are not sure why the driver drifted off the road. It could have been he was tired or was reaching for something in his Iunchbox in the passenger seat. Driver was not wearing seat belt and was ejected when the tractor flipped. The driver was found deceased at the scene and there was a"kitchen faucet" drip from the washout cap for about 3 hours. The Gilford fire department hazmat team placed a raincoat underneath the drip and used absorbent pads while trying to figure out how to remove the product. Then Fulp's Environmental Cleanup arrived and immediately placed a Bett's valve over the washout cap which stopped the spill. The original BOL had 431801bs of isobutyl acetate and the recovered tanker had 430001bs, not more than 1801bs(180/7.2lbs/G=25G) spilled. Of note, all truck scales have a weight difference, I estimate the spill to be no more than 10 gallons in three hours based on a fast kitchen faucet leak of 15,140 drips per gallon which would make it over 45000 drips in one hour(see US government website: www.water. usgs.gov/edu/activity- drip.html). The driver diesel saddle tank leaked, unknown how much. Fulp's Environmental recovered the soil based upon a Certified Geologist on scene for any spilled diesel fuel and isobutyl acetate. Isobutyl acetate is not a listed waste and the recovered soil will NOT be hazardous waste because the soil will not meet the EPA definition of D001. The wreck occurred across the street from a residential neighborhood estimated to have about 50 people living there. When the leak was discovered they were evacuated for about an hour until the leak was contained with a Bett's valve. The tanker itself did not rupture or leak. It is only the dean-out cap that was Ieaking at a drip rate. Police and fire department reports are included
column169: training of the fleet. He proceeded to develop a comprehensive Driver Safety Manual and driver safety training topics. We conduct a minimum 5-day new hire orientation trainin@ for each employee and it takes longer for the drivers to complete all the training. The driver Safety Manual is 209 pages and we train on each page. The drivers must initial and date each page that they have read and understand it as we go through the training. We already emphasize that the drivers are to follow the speed limit and to wear a seat belt anytime they are in a CMV. We also train on the the hours of service and they understand the maximum drive time is 11 hours in a 14 hour period. We have a specific presentation on this that indudes the updates to the regulation last year. We instituted a Safety Alert to which we train the employees on what happened, the potential root cause, and how to prevent a recurrence. We will continue to reinforce to the drivers NOT to be distracted when driving a CMV.

THE FAST RISING WATERS OF THE LITTLE WASIPINCON RIVER TOOK OUT THE CP RAIL BRIDGE AT MP 73 ON THE MASON CITY SUB. CP TRAIN B39-27 MOVING AT TRACK SPEED APPROACHED THE BRIDGEAND NOTICED THE BRIDGE WAS NO LONGER THERE. THE CREW ATTEMPTED TO BREAK BUT WERE UNABLE TO STOP AND WENT OFF THE TRACKS INTO THE RIVER . THE CREW WAS ABLE TO GET OUT OF THE LOCOMOTIVE AND SWIM TO A MORE STABLE AREA. THEY WERE LATER RESCUED BY NEW HAMPTON FD & CHICKASAW COUNTY RESCUE SQUAD.

Plastic jerrican was found during sort operations with a loose top. The inner content was UN3082 approximately .05 L leaked out of the jerrican before the spill agent received it. It was placed in a steel salvage drum and shipper was contacted for an amended declaration.

column168: During the PM sort operations at the FedEx Express origin station in Yuma, AZ. A fiberboard box was discovered to have a strong odor. Further investigation indicated the box contained a plastic bottle of 3.8 L of UN1203 Gasoline PG II. There were no signs of the package leaking. The involved package was placed in a salvage drum and held at the station for the customer to pick up.
